author: @UlyssesFartknocker
comment:
Love your choices all around. I do have a suggestion regarding the V20i, I'd go for the V30i instead. They have a low latency mode, lights in the front which help for early morning or night time walks, IP55 water resistance, and sound is overall nice for open ear headphones. And I got my pair for $36 on Amazon. For what you get with these that's rather impressive. 

However I feel the Aerofit 2 is among the best on this list. My only grievance with these is the overly sensitive touch controls that you'll inevitably activate when putting them on. Other than that they're quite nice. Audio is still pretty good (The base doesn't distort even at loud volumes), low latency for gaming, mics sound great for phone calls, the fit is almost as good as a single unit headset (They stay on with both my glasses and sunglasses), and the battery life is also impressive. Listened to these staying in an airport for 3 hours and I think I only went to 90%.

Open ear style headphones are neat but you generally shouldn't spend a lot of money on these. They won't have the sound quality of earbuds or over head style headphones. You're supposed to hear your surroundings easily for those who like to jog or walk outside. (Or do choirs while still hearing your environment) So my recommendations above are good for a cheap option (The V30i), or a slightly more expensive option with better fit and audio quality. (Aerofit 2)

author: @masterof2d926
comment: I got the Soundcore v20i recently for $30 and I like them, but they are still not the perfect open-earbud for me. The sound quality is really not that impressive, and even after playing around with the EQ settings, they still somehow sound worse than the no name open buds I got for $5 on Temu 😅. They also get a bit uncomfortable after a while, they are much better than any in-ears, but even after making adjustments I can't seem to find a sweet spot that lets me completely forget I'm wearing them. author: @argentum3919
comment:
I haven't listened to the blast 2, but I have listened to the original blast and the Go play 3. 
The go play 3 has a more refined sound than the original stormbox blast and every reviewer has said that the original stormbox blast is more refined than the blast 2, that is muddy
The go play 3 is very bass heavy. For me it was a little bit recessed on the trebles. Apart from the latter point, the sound is exceptionally bassy and clear. My biggest gripe with it is it only has 7 hours of battery. 
The other aspect of the stormbox blast 2 that every reviewer agrees with is that it's a very good party speaker. The go play 3 with it's nicer sound and very powerful amp is not really a party speaker.
title: TRIBIT StormBox Blast 2 Review: The PERFECT Portable Party Speaker?

author: @manjsher3094
comment:
Hi
Would be interesting if you did a sound wave test on the bass, sending only select frequencies say from 10 Hz 15 20 25 30 45 50 60 65 70 75 80 85 90 95 100 120 Hz. Doing this you would find the resonant frequencies showing you how tight or loose the bass is. Also it's a great stress test on the battery and speaker. Send a 25 Hz signal at volume through that will heat up like a toaster. Do that a few times to see how well it holds up.

For me that's information I can use, the lights well they only use battery power that is better saved for sound.

Cheers I hope to check in during the next year for your videos and reviews.

author: @jameslane2326
comment: I can not believe how hard it is to find earbuds that work for my needs, I must have very niche needs. Im looking for open ear, or in ear with ear hooks that have and LC3 dongle, 8 hours on a charge and under 100$ US. Ive scoured the internet but havent found anything, do you know of anything that fits this? If you are wondering why i need LC3 dongle, its for latency on Meta Quest 3. Apparently even though The meta quest has a Qualcomm CPU they didnt include aptx support, so when i tried the Cleer Arc 2 sport, they still had a lot of latency. I know there is a Cleer Arc 2 gaming, but the arc 2 sport was already busting my budget at 140$ I couldnt go any higher.

EarFun Uboom X spielt nochmal auf einem ganz anderen Level, insbesondere was die Mitten und Höhen angeht (sehr neutrale Abstimmung) Und durch die vielen Presets vielseitig einsetzbar. 
Der Bass ist auch nicht, wie bei vielen „Boomboxen“, schwammig, sondern sehr präzise und spielt verdammt tief. Unbedingt mal anhören!
